(17, 1, '2014-09-18 08:08:01', '2014-09-18 07:08:01', 'I had the pleasure of a cool glass of this golden ale the other day. From Thwaites of Blackburn, Lancashire, Wainwright Ale is inspired by the writer Alfred Wainwright, who would have clearly been in need of some serious refreshment after many miles pounding the paths of the Lake District, which he so memorably described in his many books on the region.\n\nAs for the beer, it was a pleasant slightly hoppy ale with a light body and a suitably refreshing finish, but I couldn''t help thinking that I preferred slurping foaming pints of Jennings Cumberland ale in a Lakeland hostelry. However, the latter beer has not been the same in my view since the involvement of Marstons''. I suppose such minor let downs seem inevitable with products like this that use nostalgia for times past as part of their marketing appeal.', 'Thwaites Wainwright Ale', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'thwaites-wainwright-ale', '', '', '2014-09-18 20:48:26', '2014-09-18 19:48:26', '', 0, 'http://comsumption.com/?p=17', 0, 'post', '', 0),
